{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502471"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:44:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:44:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1864"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1864"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.05,0.73,0.09,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1864"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33285"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1864"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1864"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18718"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"393"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7927"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8396"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35176"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42416"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/33285"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 69-year-old woman presents with a pigmented lesion under the nail of the middle finger of her left hand (Image).\u0026nbsp; This had been present for many months and she initially thought it was the result of a bruise.\u0026nbsp; She now seeks help as the nail has started to disintegrate.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Onychomycosis","Benign longitudinal melanonychia","Acral Lentiginous melanoma","Necrotic Ulcer","Onycholysis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis lesion is an \u003Cstrong\u003Eacral lentiginous melanoma, \u003C/strong\u003Ewhich is a type of melanoma that arises on the palms, soles, fingers and the toes. A common subtype is subungual melanoma (pictured above) which refers to acral lentiginous melanoma that arises from the nail bed. It can vary in colour from yellow/red to black and has poorly defined borders on the nail. As it progress it destroys the nail itself, which is suggested in the stem. Taking this into consideration, this diagnosis can be made from the clinical vignette alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnychomycosis \u003C/strong\u003Eis a subtype of tinea that is confined to the nail. These lesions are typically whitish/yellow in colour and are usually a result of dermatophyte fungi. The common features includes distal onycholysis, subungual hyperkeratosis, discoloration of the nail plate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenign longitudinal melanonychia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when melanin is deposited into the nail as it grows. This results in a discrete pigmented lesion on the nail. The pigmentation and width of the pigmentation is usually homogeneous and even throughout the nail plate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENecrotic ulcers \u003C/strong\u003Eare due to dead tissue that can present as dark brown/ black tissue with slough, pain, warmth, erythema and oedema. Given the lack of these features, this option is less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnycholysis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the detachment of the nail from the underlying skin. It can be idiopathic or secondary to trauma, chemicals or underlying infection. It typically presents whitish/ yellow with a sharply defined border between the normal and affected portions of the nail, unlike the above image.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Subungual melanoma can vary in colour from yellow/red to black and has poorly defined borders on the nail."],"references":["Oakley A. Acral lentiginous melanoma [Internet]. DermNet. 2011 [cited 2023Jan9]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/acral-lentiginous-melanoma"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18718"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1864"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19398"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19398"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ce5cbd0a-c033-4e2c-9d87-0f248fb8c48f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ce5cbd0a-c033-4e2c-9d87-0f248fb8c48f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":375}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/18718"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-03-04T11:33:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-10T09:36:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1864"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33285"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"rel